# Video 3

## Slash commands in claude

Slash commands are shortcuts you type inside claude code session, starting with /, that trigger a specific predefined action or workflow instantly — without writing out a full prompt.

There are two types of slash commands — 1. Build in commands    —     2. Custom commands

Slash commands used within any session

## Session

A session is one conversation with claude code — everything from where I run **claude to /exit.** It has a unique ID, captures the full message history, all file reads, all tools results, and current working directory. Sessions are saved automatically to **~/.claude/projets/** and can be resumed at any time, even after closing the terminal.

List down all the conversations we did —   claude -r (and you can jump into that particular session)

Resume - the session — /resume [run in any session] 

One session — one task or one feature to keep context clear

Name your session immediately — /rename [new name]

Use /btw to quick question like general question and press space bar after that answer and question will gone

To export the chat — /export file.md

/logout and /login 

## Models in Claude

1. Opus — Most powerful and expensive model for complex programming tasks and takes more tokens so use it carefully
2. Sonet —  Default  model and balanced model for day to day task 
3. Haiku — For normal and repetitive tasks and provides speed 

Use opus for planning and architecture phase and use sonet for implementation phase

Switch through model — /models 

Track usage — /usage and recharge usage — /usage-extra

/stats — for tracking 

 Generate all insights report and return as a html file — /insights 

To change configuration /config

/permissions — to utilize the permissions throughout sessions  

To change the theme — /theme 

To enable voice commands — /voice [to enable and disable]  [hold space bar while giving voice commands]

# Video 4

Use prompt from any chat bot rather than own prompt just go to chatgpt or claude to give our own prompt and he will refine that prompt and use it

To make changes in specific code file use this syntax — @folder_name/file_name — @file_name 

You can paste images in claude code
